    <text>
        <body>
            
            <div1 type="letter">
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.10.31-32_0003" />
                
                <fw type="curatorial">31</fw>
                
                <opener>
                    <dateline>
                        316 Acequica Madre
                        <hi rend="underline">Santa Fe <hi rend="caps">N.</hi> Mex.</hi>
                
                        Nov 7. 23.
                    </dateline>
                    
                    <salute>Dear Neihardt,</salute>
                </opener>
                <p>It doesn't look as tho<sic>though</sic> I could connect with you now that you are off on your jumping man performance. I'll be here until early Dec. <unclear>then</unclear> in Colorado Springs a couple of weeks + then for London. I do hope you have half the success with your lecture tour that you deserve &#8212; But in any event you have <unclear>balast</unclear> enough by this time to know popular approval signifies little or nothing tThe real satisfaction is in measuring up to your ideal of what your work should be &#8212; and then the joy of pusing the ideal higher and climbing toward that!! I envy you the <unclear>serene</unclear> joy you must find in the work you do.</p>
                    
                <p>I shall land a date for you here in Santa Fe and put Mr. <hi rend="caps">A.E.</hi> Long next to the proper parties immediately. And by the bye, I don't feel right about doing so, but in my humble opinion Mr. Long's letters are hurting you and I am going to say it. His letters to Mr. <unclear>Gast</unclear> in Pueblo (Pres. Colo Bar Assn.) <unclear>Jos.</unclear> <hi rend="caps">G.</hi> Rogers <hi rend="caps">PJN</hi> Wright in Denver, each elicited a smile because of their flowery effulgence and these men each spoke
                    
                    <pb facs="nei.j4a.10.31-32_0004"/>
                    <fw type="curatorial">34</fw>
                    
                    to me of the fact. They said that what I told them of your work was quite different from the impressions they had gotten from Mr. Long's letters. A letter to me spoke of only two great Poets&#8212; you + Tennyson! To paraphrase Whistler's remark "Why drag in Tennyson!"</p>
                    
                <p>The point of all this:&#8212; can't you have him "cut out" the saxaphone<sic>saxophone</sic> during some of the rhapsodies? Then pardon my effrontery and remember that only a deep interest would cause me to venture so.</p>
                    
                <p>I have never done a painting of an Indian battle, but soon some reproductions of my Indian series in the Bank will be available and I'll send you a series. I want to be tied up with that Song of the Indian Wars and we will manage it somehow. I used to do nothing but illustrate for 8 years and had my training with Howard Pyle.</p>
                    
                <p>Have an old adobe church for studio here and am painting "The Happy Nesting Ground" on a canvas 14' x 20' as the culminating panel of the Bank series &#8212; to be installed when the bank is enlarged. It is thrilling!</p>
               
                <p>Good luck</p>
                <closer>
                    <salute>The same</salute>
                    
                    <signed><unclear>Allen True</unclear></signed>
                </closer>
                
            </div1>
        </body>
        
